(38, 1, '2018-03-16 00:42:37', '2018-03-16 04:42:37', 'Ever since I started supporting Cinemalaya back in 2008, I’ve always been a fan of how filmmakers can make their stories the most abstract yet the most relatable. Cinemalaya films can illuminate person’s real situation through different shot angles, silent scenes and the most absurd ways to make a rendition of a situation. Say for example a scene from “Pamilyang Ordinaryo” back in 2016.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-36\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture8-1024x550.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"451\" />\n\nThe story ends with an internal shot of “Arjan” and “Jane” inside the bus after finding out that after all the hardships they have put through finding their baby, at the end they got the wrong baby. The shot did not have any dialogue rather just ambient sounds from the traffic. You see in a normal viewer’s perspective could be an opening ending and for them “what’s next for the couple?” Presumptions like that could be considered but then again in an artist’s perspective it could mean more than just a disappointment.', 'Inspired To Create Films That Touch Lives', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-autosave-v1', '', '', '2018-03-16 00:42:37', '2018-03-16 04:42:37', '', 33, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/2018/03/16/33-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(39, 1, '2018-03-16 00:42:53', '2018-03-16 04:42:53', 'Ever since I started supporting Cinemalaya back in 2008, I’ve always been a fan of how filmmakers can make their stories the most abstract yet the most relatable. Cinemalaya films can illuminate person’s real situation through different shot angles, silent scenes and the most absurd ways to make a rendition of a situation. Say for example a scene from “Pamilyang Ordinaryo” back in 2016.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-36\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture8-1024x550.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"451\" />\r\n\r\nThe story ends with an internal shot of “Arjan” and “Jane” inside the bus after finding out that after all the hardships they have put through finding their baby, at the end they got the wrong baby. The shot did not have any dialogue rather just ambient sounds from the traffic. You see in a normal viewer’s perspective could be an opening ending and for them “what’s next for the couple?” Presumptions like that could be considered but then again in an artist’s perspective it could mean more than just a disappointment.<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture9.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"960\" height=\"640\" />\r\n\r\nAs an amateur filmmaker, in the industry we consider the use of sound, space, how it was shot, characters etc. at that scene, the silence coming from the couple, the boxed space inside the bus and the shakiness coming from the bus’ movement meant more like “I give up”.  I really like this scene because personally it seems a bit cheesy to watch it and some would be annoyed but it is a scene that inspired me and say “explore more!” And these types of scenes is what I carry with as an amateur artist. These scenes that are real, relatable even by using silence can explain it all. I’ve always been taught to “never underestimate your audience”, know who you want to target in the story, as much as possible target them all. Going back to my quote for the “normal viewers”, always remember that your viewers may have different versions of “touched” just like a filmmaker making abstract scenes that in the end becomes so relatable it hits you. “Touched” for your audience could mean crying, mad, disappointment, annoyed, inspired, pity, guilt and a whole list from the emotion book. Filipinos are known for their “altruistic” characteristic we all like crying together and we feel like we are in same situations however Cinemalaya offers more than that. It offers different perspectives, allows space for multiple renditions and it is up to you and only you however you understood it and when you start thinking of all of those imaginations of scenes in your head thay when you know you’ve been “TOUCHED”. Writing a story, producing it and having a film on the big screen could be a truly inspiring moment, the same point as I have said earlier, it could be something to cry about, laugh about but at the end of your day as a filmmaker its your audience’s eyes that would tell if your story is inspiring.', 'Inspired To Create Films That Touch Lives', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-16 00:42:53', '2018-03-16 04:42:53', '', 33, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/2018/03/16/33-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
