(59, 1, '2018-03-16 01:04:01', '2018-03-16 05:04:01', 'Viewers troop to Cinemalaya year after year to witness the brave, bold and unfettered views presented by the entries, to see films crafted with the vision of the filmmaker at heart, and to witness performances by both mainstream and indie actors that often leave an indelible imprint on the minds of the moviegoers.\r\n\r\nThere is good reason why the festival heads eventually designed two full-length feature film categories for competition:\r\n\r\n“The Directors’ Showcase” is headlined by the veterans and the seasoned helmsman of the industry, with works that will not only cement their standing as true masters of Philippine cinema…\r\n\r\nBut will also give viewers a glimpse into their unadulterated vision, unhindered by the studio demands and producers’ directions and desires.\r\n\r\n“The New Breed,” on the other hand, shines the spotlight on the younger directors, with their fresh takes, maverick ways and new creative blood infusing their filmic works and language.\r\n\r\nOn top of these, there are the much-awaited Shorts, a genre that also calls for unique vision and discipline… a mastery that a filmmaker must have to completely deliver his message despite the brevity of the medium.\r\n\r\nCertainly, as can be seen in the twelve years of the festival, Cinemalaya has something for everyone.\r\n\r\nLaugh out loud humor that still drive timely and powerful messages abound in films like “ANG BABAE SA SEPTIC TANK,” “LAST SUPPER #3” and “ANG BAGONG PAMILYA NI PONCHING.”\r\n\r\nDespite the fun and hilarity, these films do not fail to make powerful statements about a variety of actually very grave subjects: filmmaking, poverty, art theft and struggling to survive within the country’s economy.\r\n\r\nHorror film fanatics have fare such as “DIPLOMAT HOTEL” while modern technology is at the heart of such films as the gritty and dark “REKORDER” and “BABAGWA,” and even in a ruminative and pensive love story like “SANA DATI.”\r\n\r\nThese films hold the attention of viewers who love figuring out the different aspects and facets of reality as they appear, veiled and unveiled by gadgets and modern-day imagery.\r\n\r\nPeople trying to figure out the workings of the minds of this generation have much to discover in films like “#Y,” a film about the millennials by a director belonging to the same demographics.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, aficionados of CINEMA itself will appreciate the behind-the scenes look at how movies are made in entries like the aforementioned “ANG BABAE SA SEPTIC TANK,” the stylish “CAMERA OBSKURA” by the award-winning Raymond Red and “EKSTRA,” a wrenching look at the life of a bit player, which ingeniously cast no less than a genuine Movie Queen, Vilma Santos, in the titular role.\r\n\r\nUrban legends and folklore are at the heart of films like “ISDA,” a take on the incredible news that arose about a woman giving birth to a real-live fish, “BACONAUA,” about mysteries in nature and the existence of a mythological creature and “TUOS,” about the ancient rituals of the Binukot.\r\n\r\nStories tackling gender are also among the most popular in Cinemalaya, such as the blockbuster “ANG PAGDADALAGA NI MAXIMO OLIVEROS,” which has continued on as a successful  stage musical, and the more somber yet also-memorable “QUICK CHANGE.”\r\n\r\nHistory buffs looking for an engaging story would love “CONCERTO,” which takes us back to World War II and how, for a moment, peace and harmony offer a break from the horrors of war during a piano concert witnessed by both a Filipino family and Japanese soldiers.\r\n\r\nMusic remains as an unbeatable tool for expression and understanding in the present day, as depicted in the festival favorites such as “SANA DINIG KITA,” “TRIBU,” and “RESPETO.”\r\n\r\nWe get to know the lives of migrant workers and Filipinos struggling overseas in movies like “HALAW” (set in Malaysia) and “TRANSIT,” with excellent performances by Irma Adlawan and a remarkable Jasmine Curtis-Smith.\r\n\r\nThese are but a few of the Cinemalaya entries I truly enjoyed with various audiences – showing how wide the range of subject matter and types of film have been featured in the festival.\r\n\r\nAdd to this the tender and often-humorous coming-of-age tale of good friends in a remote province, “PUROK 7” and the story of a modern career woman dying of a terminal illness in “100,” two entries especially memorable for me…\r\n\r\nAnd I come to realize that whatever the setting, whomever the subjects, Cinemalaya has often served to remind us that life is meant to be experienced fully, to be savored and held precious.', 'Cinemalaya is For Everyone', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '57-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-16 01:04:01', '2018-03-16 05:04:01', '', 57, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/2018/03/16/57-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(60, 1, '2018-03-16 01:04:53', '2018-03-16 05:04:53', 'I have always wondered how FlipTop became a trend in the Philippines. From what I understand, Flip top is when Filipino rappers exchange rhyming insults to one another. It is a competition between who is wittier and more eloquent. A year ago, I have come across watching a Cinemala film entitled Respeto. Directed by Treb Monteras II, he was able to give the audiences a story much more than just about rap battles. It\'s about a boy named Hendrix who was born and raised in the slums. He did not have his parents but only lived with his drug addict big sister, and her drug dealer boyfriend who has sex almost the whole time they were being shown in the scenes. Eventually, Hendrix realizes that life is not at all fun and games when he comes across a retired poet, he will be the reason behind great life lessons that will be enough for Hendrix to change his ways and become a better person. There are reasons why I believe that this film became a huge impact in my life and these are just a few:\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Exceptionally good raps.</b></strong>\r\n\r\nThe lyrics of what was featured in the film have really given me such an amusement and respect to rappers. Being a 20 year old lady who have only fancied western rappers, It was a huge surprise for me to understand and fully digest the lyrics of each verses. It was though as if they were reciting their raps in a very casual and impromptu matter (although I know that it was written and was prepared even before they have started shooting the movie).\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Realistic Mise en Scene </b></strong>\r\n\r\nMr. Monteras was able to capture the disturbing environment of the slums that we have no intention of appreciating in mainstream films, but at the same time, he was able to artistically move around and play with the angles of which the milieu is interesting enough to captivate. The film also presented the ways of the war on drugs, which was very timely and relevant in the country. Soon enough, the little scenes such as rading the accused drug dealers and users and demolish their houses afterwards were a part of the film. This was something i would never forget because Hendrix\'s brother-in-law suddenly forces him to pee in a plastic because the police were about to rade them. Next thing he knows, his sister and his brother in law panics and he accidentally touches the poop in the plastic he was holding- Yuck!\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Revolves around the rap culture.</b></strong>\r\n\r\nOf course, the life inside and outside of rapping was the focus on most of the scenes the film. It gave me an impression that Flip Top is no game and a hobby of wanna-be hip-hop Filipino groups is an art form that entails practice, word power, and excellence. The approach of adding a veteran poet in the character made the film much more interesting because I was able to compare and contrast rapping in the modern era and the classics of <em><i>pakikipagbalagtasan </i></em>in other words poetic competition.\r\n\r\nThese are only a few things that I have noticed in the film and are the causes of which I never thought would make me view Flip Top in a different way. It has made me become more open with what I think is <em><i>baduy </i></em>and has changed my perspective in the different art forms of rap battle.', 'Respeto as an Eyeopener', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'respeto-as-an-eyeopener', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:39:53', '2018-03-20 14:39:53', '', 0, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/?p=60', 0, 'post', '', 0),
