(132, 1, '2018-03-19 09:06:15', '2018-03-19 13:06:15', 'A Classic cinemalaya film from back in 2005, Ang Pagdadalaga ni Maximo Oliveros is a beautiful film by Auraeous Solito. A 12 year old Maximo Oliveros is from the slums in Manila. Maximo, lovingly referred to by his neighbors as Maxi, is gay. Despite his traditionally unaccepted sexual orientation, he is tenderly taken care of by his doting father and two older brothers. Maxi\'s family is engaged in a life of crime and monkey business ranging from peddling illegal drugs to pick-pocketing cellular phones. Personally, this film is the most remarkable LGBT related movie I’ve ever seen. And I wasn’t the only one with the same sentiments. Its influence was so widespread that they had to show and bring it to Manhattan for international screening. In a nutshell, it talks about how a young boy can live his life normally without the oftentimes heavy burden of hiding one’s sexuality. This story brings out a very powerful voice for the LGBT community wherein it showed the complexity of the elements involved in the concepts of “homosexuality” and “ innocence”. These complexities were highlighted in the simple story of a young boy exposed to corruption and despondency. Maxi showed truthfulness and heart all throughout the film. It speaks toward a reality we live in now, which wasn’t the case at the time. The reality being that one’s sexual orientation is not “just a phase” and doesn’t need to affect the way people around you interact with you. Maxi is not defined by his sexuality, but simply by his person and everyone around him treats him as exactly what he is - a good, and honest little boy. There are no formal rites of passage, no overly elaborate plot that pushes him to grow up and out of his puppy love feelings for the policeman he has a crush on. Audiences may misunderstand the title “The Blossoming”, however in the story Maxi\'s metamorphic blossoming results from what essentially is an innocent crush that curiously develops into an ambiguous attraction. This being from the very first Cinemalaya film festival, was a brave move considering the social climate of the Philippines toward LGBT culture at the time. For many years, being “bakla” or “tomboy” in Philippine media would always have a comedic connotation - the overly rambunctious cross-dressing gay and the virgin tomboy awaiting a real man’s touch. And for many years, this form of “toleration” of the LGBT community was all the representation there was in Philippine society. But through films like this, the truth of the LGBT community’s story is brought out of the shadows and onto the silver screen for all to open their eyes. It is thanks to this movie that many more entries into the Cinemalaya film festival were able to be transparent about sexuality - a most taboo discussion for a traditionally Catholic country. Especially through the perspective of an innocent child just going through life, experiencing every “normal” encounter in a young person’s life - like a simple crush. This simply told story about a little crush will always represent the truth of humanity - no matter who we are and where we come from we all deserve to love.', 'How Brave, Maxi', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-brave-maxi', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:42:01', '2018-03-20 14:42:01', '', 0, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/?p=132', 0, 'post', '', 0),
