(147, 1, '2018-03-20 10:07:54', '2018-03-20 14:07:54', '<style>.entry-header {display: none;}</style>\r\n<h1 style=\"font-size: 2.75rem; font-family: Montserrat, \"Helvetica Neue\", sans-serif;     font-weight: 700;\r\n    line-height: 1.25;\"><center><strong>Subscription Policy</strong></center></h1>\r\n“Through the Eyes” is an E Magazine that enlightens its readers to the different views of authors that share the interest with Cinemalaya Film Festival. In line with this, the subject of each article consists of their different perspectives through their eyes as an audience, a director or an actor. This is used only as a medium to further understand and digest the highlighted socially relevant films. Furthermore, the contents of this material shall; willingly share to its readers and be used as a guide to future researchers or enthusiasts but only when the author is acknowledged., not encourage any plagiarism of any kind so as to respect the author\'s personal insights and views on any particular matter, and, maintain professionalism by refraining from libellous or otherwise unlawful, abusive or obscene material.\r\n\r\nFor the benefit of the subscriber, any information needed will not be released to the public or any third party without permission from the user or as required by law. It will remain private so as to respect the individual\'s human right of privacy. The subscriber will also acquire his/her animosity to be able to freely accept it\'s requests and comments to further improve the future E-magazines that will be published.', 'Subscription Policy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '145-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:07:54', '2018-03-20 14:07:54', '', 145, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/145-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(148, 1, '2018-03-20 10:08:43', '2018-03-20 14:08:43', '<style>.entry-header {display: none;}</style>\r\n<h1 style=\"font-size: 2.75rem; font-family: Montserrat, \"Helvetica Neue\", sans-serif;     font-weight: 700;\r\n    line-height: 1.25;\"><center><strong>Advertising Policy</strong></center></h1>\r\nThe views and opinions written by contributors and images utilized in the E-magazine entitled “Through The Eyes” do not necessarily reflect or represent the views of the proponent. “Through The Eyes” E-magazine and its contributors are not associated, connected nor affiliated with Cinemalaya Film Festival organizers and do not reflect or represent the said entity. For clarifications, this medium is for the soul purpose of only an academic requirement. The articles that are included in this medium may contain content copyrighted by another entity or person. It involves the given permission of each contributor by expressing their own personal point of view of the Cinemalaya Film Festival and wishes to promote the films that are locally made and produced. \r\n\r\nThe contents of this E- Magazine is limited and shall not be limited to: Informing the youth of the social relevance of the articles, Spreading awareness to the youth about societal issues represented by the films, and encouraging the youth to support Cinemalaya films presented available only in the Philippines. The stated objectives are only the ideal goal of the editor but does not confirm that this E- Magazine is a promotional material of the Cinemalaya Film Festival. This E-Magazine targets Male and Female ages 18 to 25 years old, preferably those who are in High School, College, Aspiring Filmmakers and individuals who are a part of the film and art industry. \r\n\r\nThe contents of the material do not impose on any insult directed to whatever is stated but are just subjective opinions by the writer. The editor of this E-Magazine publishes what is ought to be given attention to in order to enlighten the readers. The interpretation by the reader of the articles may acquire contradicting views based on their own personal standing but are free to determine for themselves what to accept or reject. Moreover, the contents of this E-Magazine highlight each contributor\'s freedom of speech but do not accept any libelous statements in order to maintain professionalism in the material. Lastly, ethics and practicality are still present throughout the making of each article about how the writers are free of expressing their own thoughts, suggestions and opinions without shaming any third party for that matter.', 'Advertising Policy', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '116-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:08:43', '2018-03-20 14:08:43', '', 116, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/116-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(149, 1, '2018-03-20 10:37:13', '2018-03-20 14:37:13', 'Ang pelikula ay isang pamamaraan ng pagpapahayag ng pananaw at damdamin ng mga gumagawa nito. Kapag ako ay lumilikha ng pelikula ang nasasaloob sa mga ito ay ang pananaw ko sa mundo, sa ating bansa at ang mga kaisipan at damdamin na nais kong maipahayag, mailabas, at maibahigi sa mga manonood nito.\r\n\r\nAng una kong pelikula na naisali sa film festival ay ang “North Diversion Road” sa Cinema One Orignals dahil noong unang dalawang taon na magsimula ang Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival taong 2005 at 2006, empleyado ako ng Cultural Center of the Philippines — ang ibig sabihin nito ay hindi ako maaring sumali sa kanilang film festival. Noong ako ay natapos magtrabaho sa CCP, dumating ang pagkakataon ko na makapagpasa ng aking nagawang pelikula sa kanila. Ang unang ginawa ko para sa Cinemalaya ay ang pamagat nito ay “Tukso” — isa siyang thriller. Tungkol ito sa kwento ng isang babae na pinatay at ang hinahanap ay kung sino ang may kagagawan sa kanyang kamatayan. Ang pahayag ng mga hurado sa taon na sumali ako sa Cinemalaya ay nagustuhan nila sa “Tukso” ay kung paano pinakikita ang mga karakter ng mga tauhan sa paraan na inilalahad din yung kwento at ung onti-unti kang nadadala doon sa pelikula dahil ang kwento ay kung papaano malalaman sino ang may kagagawan sa pagkamatay ng isang karakter.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-6\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture1.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"333\" />\r\n\r\nDalawang pelikula ang ipinasa ko sa Cinemalaya, ang isa ay tungkol sa isang kandidato sa eleksyon, ang pamagat nito ay “Vox Populi”, at isa naman yung sa “Tukso”. Ang “Vox Populi” ay hindi katwiran na nakapaloob sa social concern bagamat ang paraan ng pagpapakita at pinapapahayag ko sa loob ng kwento at sa pagagawa ng pelikula, pinalabas ko yung realidad ng mga tao sa kata na lugar na kinapapalooban ng kwento. Ang “Vox Populi” ay tungkol naman sa isang kandidato. Tatlong taon ang nakalipas, pagkaraan, muli kong sinulat. Ang pelikula na ito ay ang natanggap sa Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival 6. Ang “Vox Populi” ay maliwanag na nangangatwiran mayroon social concern dahil talagang batay ang kuwento sa totoong karakter ko bilang isang campaign aid sa kampanya sa politika. Ang nakapaloob sa “Vox Populi” ay ibintay sa totoong mga pangyayari. Nakakatawa dito, mayroong dating isang gobernador ng isang probinsya na nakapanood ng aking pelikula at kanyang pinahayag ay tunay at katotohanan ang mga nangyayari sa pelikula na \"Vox Populi\".\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-10\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture4-1024x768.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"525\" height=\"394\" />\r\n\r\nMaaga ako nagsimula na magtrabaho sa teatro at sa pelikula. Noong magsimula ako, hindi pa ako nakatapos sa pag-aaral. Labing-pitong gulang ako noong magtrabaho ako sa industriya ng mainstream na pelikula. Noong nagkaron na ng tinatawag nating \"Digital Revolution” naging mas madali gumawa ng pelikula. Naisipan kong magkaron ng pagkakataon na gumawa ng mga pelikula dahil mayroon akong nais ipahayag, meron akong mga nais na ibahagi sa mga tatangkilik na aking mga gawa. Nagpapasalamat ako sa mga festivals na kagaya ng “Cinema One Originals” at ng “Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival”, nakapagpasa ako ng proyekto na nagkaron ng pagkakataong magawa  ang mga pelikula na ito.', 'Mensahe ng Pelikula sa mga Pilipino', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '5-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:37:13', '2018-03-20 14:37:13', '', 5, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/5-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(150, 1, '2018-03-20 10:37:33', '2018-03-20 14:37:33', 'Ang Cinemalaya ay isa sa mga pinakamahalagang naganap sa pelikula ng Pilipinas sa nakaraang labing-limang taon. Sa Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival nagkaron ng pagkakataon ang mga maraming director na maglahad at magpahayag ng kanilang mga kuwento. Kapag hihintayin natin ang mainstream, matagal pa ito mangyayari. Bukod pa, ang mga pelikula na ipinalabas sa Cinemalaya, at dahil sa kalidad ng mga pelikulang pinalabas sa film festival na ito, marami sa mga festival programmers sa buong mundo ang hinihintay ang mga pelikulang ilalabas sa Cinemalaya.\r\n\r\nHindi pa natatapos film festival, iniimbita na ng mga festival programmers mula sa ibang bansa ang mga pelikula na ipinapalabas sa Cinemalaya para isali sa kanilang sariling paligsahan. Ito ay mga international na film festival, katulad ng Berlin International Film Festival, Venice International Film Festival, Tokyo International Film Festival, Busan International Film Festival, at iba pa. Sa mga filmmakers na nakakaalam kung paano umaandar ang  mga festivals, isang itong malaki at mahalaga na bagay. Unang una, ang mga film festivals, mga programmers, at mga festival directors, patuloy na naghahanap ng magaganda at makabubuluhang mga pelikula. Nagpapasa rin ang  iba marami upang mapili, ngunit ang mga festival programmers ang nag dumadayo sa ating bansa upang sila ay makapili ng mga pelikulang maisasali nila sa kanilang film festival.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-51\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/insert3.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"960\" height=\"418\" />\r\n\r\nHindi pa nagwawakas ang Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival, may imbitasyon na makasali sa mga intenational film festivals ang ibang mga pelikula, halimbawa, sa nakaraang Cinemalaya 13, ang “Baconaua” na inilikha ni Director Joseph Israel Laban ay nananalo ng Special Jury Award at Best Cinematography ay naimbitahan agad ito sa Busan International Film Festival. Malaking bagay na nakakaharap ng filmmakers ang mga festival programmers dahil nagkakaron ng pagkakataon ang mga pelikula na gawa ng mga Pilipino na mapanood ng mga ibang mamamayan na hindi taga rito sa ating bansa. Nagkakaroon sila ng  mga bagong pananaw tungkol sa pagkatao ng mga Pilipino sa mga pamamagitan ng mga pelikula na pinalalabas, kagaya na rin ang magandang nangyayari dito sa atin. Marami sanang manonood ng mga pelikulang galing sa Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival o mga iba pang film festivals na mayroon tayo sa bansa dahil ang mga kuwentong kanilang ipinakikita ay hindi mga karaniwang kuwento na napapanood natin ng katulad sa industriya ng mainstream cinema bagamat hindi lahat, pero malimit na kapag mainstream,  ang nakikita natin ay love story, o kaya\'y kwento ng isang karakter na inabuso at naghirap; pagkatapos ay magtatagumpay sa huli — malimit ito ang kwento ng mga pelikula na nasasaloob sa mainstream cinema. Ngunit para sa akin, hindi lang sa mga aspetong ibinabahagi ng mainstream ang kuwento ng karaniwang Pilipino. Sa mga pinapalabas ng Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival, nakikita natin ang mga kwento ng hindi lang ng mga taga-Maynila kundi ng iba pang mga kababayan natin na nagmumula sa ibang panig ng Pilipinas, at mga buhay ng ibang mga tao na kung minsan ay hindi magihawa.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-18\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture6.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"820\" height=\"461\" />\r\n\r\nSa mga sumusuporta sa Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival, sana ay ipagpatuloy ninyo ang pagtangkilik sa pelikulang ito. Para sa mga manonood ng pelikula, sana ipagpatuloy ninyo ang suporta na inyong nilalaan para sa sining; at para sa mga hindi pa nagkakaroon ng pagkakataong makanood, taon-taon nagaganap ang Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival, sana makanood kayo habang pinapalabas o kaya’y gumawa ng paraan upang magkaroon ng pagkakataong mapanood ang mga pelikula galing sa Cinemalaya at sa iba pang mga festival na kagaya nito.', 'Ang Galing ng Pelikulang Pinoy: Cinemalaya Films Go International', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '16-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:37:33', '2018-03-20 14:37:33', '', 16, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/16-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(151, 1, '2018-03-20 10:37:57', '2018-03-20 14:37:57', 'Ever since I started supporting Cinemalaya back in 2008, I’ve always been a fan of how filmmakers can make their stories the most abstract yet the most relatable. Cinemalaya films can illuminate person’s real situation through different shot angles, silent scenes and the most absurd ways to make a rendition of a situation. Say for example a scene from “Pamilyang Ordinaryo” back in 2016.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-36\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture8-1024x550.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"451\" />\r\n\r\nThe story ends with an internal shot of “Arjan” and “Jane” inside the bus after finding out that after all the hardships they have put through finding their baby, at the end they got the wrong baby. The shot did not have any dialogue rather just ambient sounds from the traffic. You see in a normal viewer’s perspective could be an opening ending and for them “what’s next for the couple?” Presumptions like that could be considered but then again in an artist’s perspective it could mean more than just a disappointment.<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-37\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture9.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"960\" height=\"640\" />\r\n\r\nAs an amateur filmmaker, in the industry we consider the use of sound, space, how it was shot, characters etc. at that scene, the silence coming from the couple, the boxed space inside the bus and the shakiness coming from the bus’ movement meant more like “I give up”.  I really like this scene because personally it seems a bit cheesy to watch it and some would be annoyed but it is a scene that inspired me and say “explore more!” And these types of scenes is what I carry with as an amateur artist. These scenes that are real, relatable even by using silence can explain it all. I’ve always been taught to “never underestimate your audience”, know who you want to target in the story, as much as possible target them all. Going back to my quote for the “normal viewers”, always remember that your viewers may have different versions of “touched” just like a filmmaker making abstract scenes that in the end becomes so relatable it hits you. “Touched” for your audience could mean crying, mad, disappointment, annoyed, inspired, pity, guilt and a whole list from the emotion book. Filipinos are known for their “altruistic” characteristic we all like crying together and we feel like we are in same situations however Cinemalaya offers more than that. It offers different perspectives, allows space for multiple renditions and it is up to you and only you however you understood it and when you start thinking of all of those imaginations of scenes in your head thay when you know you’ve been “TOUCHED”. Writing a story, producing it and having a film on the big screen could be a truly inspiring moment, the same point as I have said earlier, it could be something to cry about, laugh about but at the end of your day as a filmmaker its your audience’s eyes that would tell if your story is inspiring.', 'Inspired To Create Films That Touch Lives', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '33-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:37:57', '2018-03-20 14:37:57', '', 33, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/33-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(152, 1, '2018-03-20 10:38:37', '2018-03-20 14:38:37', 'I have always enjoyed making films that touch on the social aspect of what is happening right now in our society. It is always a commentary on how ludicrous or how weird everything is starting to become. What used to be uncanny and unacceptable, at least 10 or 20 years ago, is the “new normal”. In my film Donor (2010), the act of selling one’s organ for 100,000 pesos that is a part of you, your identity, and who you are is just \"normal”.  I always begin the concepts of my film by looking and exploring around unusual jobs. It actually started when I read about a job called “organ transporter”, which is actually a legal job. This is a job that is being practiced in the United States and Mexico.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-42\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture11-1024x682.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"559\" />\r\n\r\nThe responsibility of this person is to transport organs for emergency and operations. Do you imagine the moral issues that you deal with moving organs? When I started writing the script and doing research, I have studied that the Philippines is the third country in the whole world with the biggest issue of \"organ trafficking” — First is China, second is India, and third comes the Philippines. I thought it was shocking that many people in the Philippines are selling their organs for a price. When i started telling and sharing to people what about my research and idea for the film, I spoke to Joel Lamangan and he said “Go to Baseco. There are a lot of people there who have sold their organs” and I asked him “Paano ko malalaman? You don’t just go there.” and Joel replied “No, no. just go there”, and so I did. I went to Baseco and looked for the barangay captain. True enough I told the barangay captain that i needed to interview someone who has sold their kidney for a fee and he told me, “Madali lang yan. Halika, sumama ka sa akin” . We went to the Gawad Kalinga village in Baseco, he knocked on the first door and surprisingly the person who happened to live there already sold his kidney. Imagine how many people who reside in Baseco has sold their kidneys for a price. Apparently 90% of the pedicab drivers in Baseco have sold a kidney 7 or 8 years ago.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-large wp-image-43\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture12-1024x682.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"840\" height=\"559\" />\r\n\r\nEach one of them has different prices and varying stories. The sad thing is after the operation has been conducted, they have sold what they think is a huge amount of money costing 100,000 pesos. They were caught off guard. After a year, the 100,000 pesos was already spent. They did not have anything to show. They think that their lives will be normal but it wouldn\'t for the reason that they are more prone to sickness like high blood pressure and they are more susceptible to diseases because they lost an organ in their system. At the same time, smoking and drinking is prohibited to people who have donated their kidneys because their resistance is weaker compared to when they still had both. It is like we do not know what is \"normal\" anymore.', 'What is Normal?: Organ Trafficking in the Philippines', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '40-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:38:37', '2018-03-20 14:38:37', '', 40, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/40-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(153, 1, '2018-03-20 10:39:02', '2018-03-20 14:39:02', 'Intrinsic in the Festival title is the implication that “CINEMA IS A CATALYST FOR FREEDOM,” or that “THESE MOVIES ARE THE PRODUCT OF MINDS AND CREATIVE FORCES THAT ARE FREE TO EXPLORE, TO PRESENT REALITIES AND VARIOUS FACETS OF IT, TO CALL PEOPLE AND SOCIETY TO CHANGE.”\r\n\r\nDevoid of the usual hindrances of regulation and censorship, the festival guidelines give the filmmakers and artists creative freedom to flesh out and present their entries.\r\n\r\nIn the entries that have comprised the festivals from 2005 to 2017, many of the themes were, indeed, crafted to serve as eye-openers to various aspects of our realities in these present times.\r\n\r\nAnd most of these films did not stop at being agents of enlightenment. By bringing to the fore these realities in our consciousness, they all make a dramatic, hard-hitting, provocative and urgent call to ACTION.\r\n\r\nNow that their films have made us aware of the plight of these people, often living below the radar of our day-to-day routines, the filmmakers have given these people a voice, one that we cannot ignore in the face of our pressing everyday concerns.\r\n\r\nSome of these films are cited here, not for their outstanding qualities as motion pictures (although some of these are, certainly, excellent films) but for their content and subject matter which constitute the call for action and for change – in society, in governance, in our mindsets as a people who must be made aware that these conditions and realities exist – and that this knowledge should serve to move us to take action.\r\n\r\nPOVERTY and the ECONOMY force the characters in some Cinemalaya entries to go through harrowing actions, make tough decisions and is the reason why they find themselves embroiled in situations that are unforgettable for the viewers.\r\n\r\n“DONOR” was about a woman who is forced to donate a part of her body in order to make ends meet, while “PAMILYA ORDINARYO” gave viewers a closer look at what it’s like for a very young couple of street kids to have – and lose – their baby in the busy, cold and hard metropolis they themselves must navigate as hardened young survivors.\r\n\r\n“SAMPAGUITA” was also a window into the lives of the kids we see everyday darting in and out of busy streets to sell garlands for the motorists’ cars.\r\n\r\n“ENDO” was a rumination on how the work force of this country must bite the bullet and accept employment that gives them little in terms of security and a future that would sustain them as gainfully-employed individuals in the long term. Set against a love story framework, the film actually has as its core the current workers’ seemingly unending quest for permanence, stability and security – in life, as in love, not to keep flitting in and out of engagements that always come to a halt at the “end of contract.”\r\n\r\n“DONSOL” is A CALL FOR ENVIRONMENTAL AWARENESS and the PRESERVATION that also makes use of a potent romantic storyline and exquisite cinematography to highlight the magnificence and the threats to their existence faced by the whale sharks.\r\n\r\nThe seemingly MARGINALIZED YOUTH is likewise the subject of Cinemalaya entries like “TRIBU.” Focusing on the tough-talking and tough-living Tondo kids who find a sense of brotherhood in their gangs and whose outlet is fliptop rap and street showdowns, I recall director Jim Libiran pleading with the Tondo policemen to desist from picking and locking up the Tondo boys indiscriminately during his acceptance speech on awards night. He pointed out that some of these so-called “habitual offenders” were actually onstage that night, receiving acclaim for the film they starred in and starting to make a life of honor, recognition and purpose.\r\n\r\nThe youth of the country need saving, indeed, according to some Cinemalaya entries. And not only on the streets of Manila, but also in the countryside.\r\n\r\nThis was the focus of “ANG GURO KONG DI MARUNONG MAGBASA,” a violent treatise on how mere children are recruited into armies, taught to bear and use firearms, and to kill.\r\n\r\nAnd in “ASINTADO,” Nueva Ecija is the setting wherein a teenager botches a drug courier job he is forced to take on, mobilizing his mother and younger brother, a sharpshooting child suffering from autism, to go on a suspenseful mission to save him from the ringleaders.\r\n\r\n“TAKLUB” featured great actress Nora Aunor in the center of a piece tackling the effects of Typhoon Yolanda.\r\n\r\nTragedy and drama are not the only vehicles that Cinemalaya entries have employed through all its years of existence, comedy and satire have also effectively sounded their own call to action in the festival – most notably in “ANG BABAE SA SEPTIC TANK.”\r\n\r\nThis film employs everything including a movie-within-a-movie device to posit the superbly engaging and hard-hitting “poverty porn” theme that is said to fuel interest of foreign film festivals in some of our locally-produced films. The humor, in the end, is what makes this film even more effective in highlighting the NEED to improve the quality of life of people in our society.\r\n\r\nThese are but a few films that were part of Cinemalaya in various years – all depicting the realities that we must be made aware of, examine and strive to change… for the better.', 'Cinemalaya is a Wake-Up Call To All Filipinos: It’s Time To Change', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '45-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:39:02', '2018-03-20 14:39:02', '', 45, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/45-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(154, 1, '2018-03-20 10:39:19', '2018-03-20 14:39:19', 'Viewers troop to Cinemalaya year after year to witness the brave, bold and unfettered views presented by the entries, to see films crafted with the vision of the filmmaker at heart, and to witness performances by both mainstream and indie actors that often leave an indelible imprint on the minds of the moviegoers.\r\n\r\nThere is good reason why the festival heads eventually designed two full-length feature film categories for competition:\r\n\r\n“The Directors’ Showcase” is headlined by the veterans and the seasoned helmsman of the industry, with works that will not only cement their standing as true masters of Philippine cinema…\r\n\r\nBut will also give viewers a glimpse into their unadulterated vision, unhindered by the studio demands and producers’ directions and desires.\r\n\r\n“The New Breed,” on the other hand, shines the spotlight on the younger directors, with their fresh takes, maverick ways and new creative blood infusing their filmic works and language.\r\n\r\nOn top of these, there are the much-awaited Shorts, a genre that also calls for unique vision and discipline… a mastery that a filmmaker must have to completely deliver his message despite the brevity of the medium.\r\n\r\nCertainly, as can be seen in the twelve years of the festival, Cinemalaya has something for everyone.\r\n\r\nLaugh out loud humor that still drive timely and powerful messages abound in films like “ANG BABAE SA SEPTIC TANK,” “LAST SUPPER #3” and “ANG BAGONG PAMILYA NI PONCHING.”\r\n\r\nDespite the fun and hilarity, these films do not fail to make powerful statements about a variety of actually very grave subjects: filmmaking, poverty, art theft and struggling to survive within the country’s economy.\r\n\r\nHorror film fanatics have fare such as “DIPLOMAT HOTEL” while modern technology is at the heart of such films as the gritty and dark “REKORDER” and “BABAGWA,” and even in a ruminative and pensive love story like “SANA DATI.”\r\n\r\nThese films hold the attention of viewers who love figuring out the different aspects and facets of reality as they appear, veiled and unveiled by gadgets and modern-day imagery.\r\n\r\nPeople trying to figure out the workings of the minds of this generation have much to discover in films like “#Y,” a film about the millennials by a director belonging to the same demographics.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, aficionados of CINEMA itself will appreciate the behind-the scenes look at how movies are made in entries like the aforementioned “ANG BABAE SA SEPTIC TANK,” the stylish “CAMERA OBSKURA” by the award-winning Raymond Red and “EKSTRA,” a wrenching look at the life of a bit player, which ingeniously cast no less than a genuine Movie Queen, Vilma Santos, in the titular role.\r\n\r\nUrban legends and folklore are at the heart of films like “ISDA,” a take on the incredible news that arose about a woman giving birth to a real-live fish, “BACONAUA,” about mysteries in nature and the existence of a mythological creature and “TUOS,” about the ancient rituals of the Binukot.\r\n\r\nStories tackling gender are also among the most popular in Cinemalaya, such as the blockbuster “ANG PAGDADALAGA NI MAXIMO OLIVEROS,” which has continued on as a successful  stage musical, and the more somber yet also-memorable “QUICK CHANGE.”\r\n\r\nHistory buffs looking for an engaging story would love “CONCERTO,” which takes us back to World War II and how, for a moment, peace and harmony offer a break from the horrors of war during a piano concert witnessed by both a Filipino family and Japanese soldiers.\r\n\r\nMusic remains as an unbeatable tool for expression and understanding in the present day, as depicted in the festival favorites such as “SANA DINIG KITA,” “TRIBU,” and “RESPETO.”\r\n\r\nWe get to know the lives of migrant workers and Filipinos struggling overseas in movies like “HALAW” (set in Malaysia) and “TRANSIT,” with excellent performances by Irma Adlawan and a remarkable Jasmine Curtis-Smith.\r\n\r\nThese are but a few of the Cinemalaya entries I truly enjoyed with various audiences – showing how wide the range of subject matter and types of film have been featured in the festival.\r\n\r\nAdd to this the tender and often-humorous coming-of-age tale of good friends in a remote province, “PUROK 7” and the story of a modern career woman dying of a terminal illness in “100,” two entries especially memorable for me…\r\n\r\nAnd I come to realize that whatever the setting, whomever the subjects, Cinemalaya has often served to remind us that life is meant to be experienced fully, to be savored and held precious.', 'Cinemalaya is For Everyone', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '57-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:39:19', '2018-03-20 14:39:19', '', 57, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/57-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(155, 1, '2018-03-20 10:39:53', '2018-03-20 14:39:53', 'I have always wondered how FlipTop became a trend in the Philippines. From what I understand, Flip top is when Filipino rappers exchange rhyming insults to one another. It is a competition between who is wittier and more eloquent. A year ago, I have come across watching a Cinemala film entitled Respeto. Directed by Treb Monteras II, he was able to give the audiences a story much more than just about rap battles. It\'s about a boy named Hendrix who was born and raised in the slums. He did not have his parents but only lived with his drug addict big sister, and her drug dealer boyfriend who has sex almost the whole time they were being shown in the scenes. Eventually, Hendrix realizes that life is not at all fun and games when he comes across a retired poet, he will be the reason behind great life lessons that will be enough for Hendrix to change his ways and become a better person. There are reasons why I believe that this film became a huge impact in my life and these are just a few:\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Exceptionally good raps.</b></strong>\r\n\r\nThe lyrics of what was featured in the film have really given me such an amusement and respect to rappers. Being a 20 year old lady who have only fancied western rappers, It was a huge surprise for me to understand and fully digest the lyrics of each verses. It was though as if they were reciting their raps in a very casual and impromptu matter (although I know that it was written and was prepared even before they have started shooting the movie).\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Realistic Mise en Scene </b></strong>\r\n\r\nMr. Monteras was able to capture the disturbing environment of the slums that we have no intention of appreciating in mainstream films, but at the same time, he was able to artistically move around and play with the angles of which the milieu is interesting enough to captivate. The film also presented the ways of the war on drugs, which was very timely and relevant in the country. Soon enough, the little scenes such as rading the accused drug dealers and users and demolish their houses afterwards were a part of the film. This was something i would never forget because Hendrix\'s brother-in-law suddenly forces him to pee in a plastic because the police were about to rade them. Next thing he knows, his sister and his brother in law panics and he accidentally touches the poop in the plastic he was holding- Yuck!\r\n\r\n<strong><b>Revolves around the rap culture.</b></strong>\r\n\r\nOf course, the life inside and outside of rapping was the focus on most of the scenes the film. It gave me an impression that Flip Top is no game and a hobby of wanna-be hip-hop Filipino groups is an art form that entails practice, word power, and excellence. The approach of adding a veteran poet in the character made the film much more interesting because I was able to compare and contrast rapping in the modern era and the classics of <em><i>pakikipagbalagtasan </i></em>in other words poetic competition.\r\n\r\nThese are only a few things that I have noticed in the film and are the causes of which I never thought would make me view Flip Top in a different way. It has made me become more open with what I think is <em><i>baduy </i></em>and has changed my perspective in the different art forms of rap battle.', 'Respeto as an Eyeopener', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:39:53', '2018-03-20 14:39:53', '', 60, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/60-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(156, 1, '2018-03-20 10:40:12', '2018-03-20 14:40:12', 'The harsh reality of what we call \"poverty- pornographic\" about Eduardo Roy Jr.\'s Pamilya Ordinaryo was a vivid representation that was meticulously written and produced. Think of it this way: Two kids living in the streets of Manila have themselves a new-born baby, gets stolen by a seemingly generous male cross dresser and searches for their missing child. Through the journey, they experience disgusting maltreatment from the police (who should be the first ones to help them), criminal acts, a news feature, and false hopes.\r\n\r\nFor those individuals who are afraid to experience first hand or even witness minors doing drugs, stealing, robbing, and cursing as their language in locations such as marketplaces, street corners, tunnels and bridges- this is not at all an imagination and is a nightmare to passersby.\r\n\r\nWhat is oddly interesting is that, while this is the continuous issue running in the country, it is still unrecognized and shrugged off by the people of who can help prevent these unfortunate events. The film added the CCTV footages as a tool to depict the reality of which we ourselves may be unaware of and is already happening. The power of the film being able to shamelessly let its audience feel disturbed is very effective.\r\n\r\nThe starring couple, Jane and Aries is presented as a very mischievous duo. To survive a day they have no choice but to do reckless activities such as pickpocketing, having sex, screaming, sleeping, fighting but despite of it all, they are each other\'s strong foundation and manage to deal with each other as family. The scenes in the film produced a number of metaphors that is timely to the social and economic situation of the Philippines under the brackets C and D.\r\n\r\nThroughout the long feature- and aside from the vulgar scenes about hypocrisy, unjust and abusive social and governmental institutions that supposedly help and protect the poor and the oppressed, the couple have been the main focus of the evidences of these truths because as hard and difficult as it is to digest the story, it is always a taboo that we wish we could change.\r\n\r\nFor someone who has only started watching Cinemalaya films for only 3 years and counting, this is the only film that has been very moving and has achieved to raise- consciousness to the Filipino audience. The vulgar representation of what the title means by Pamilya Ordinaryo depicts an ironic theme due to the several consecutive unfortunate events that had happened to the starring couple. The disheartening realization after viewing the film is how society do not give so much importance to the point wherein it has become the biggest taboo in the country, which makes it a spectacular- touching film.\r\n\r\nThe reason behind a great admiration for the film is that it showed a very authentic and raw situation of the life of poor teenage parents who were victimized by their family, agents of the police, media, local government, heartless pranksters. There were various scenes that made the audiences react so violently that is enough proof that Pamilya Ordinaryo was well deserving of its claimed awards by many competitions.', 'Nothing Ordinary in Pamilya Ordinaryo', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '63-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:40:12', '2018-03-20 14:40:12', '', 63, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/63-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(157, 1, '2018-03-20 10:40:46', '2018-03-20 14:40:46', 'In 2009, I had a meet-up in a coffee shop in San Juan with La Salle alumnus and writer-producer-actor-director Mike Sandejas. He was embarking on another Cinemalaya project, three years after winning the Balanghai trophy for his film about iconic rock band, The Dawn, in 2006 (“Tulad ng Dati”).\r\n\r\nHe was offering me the role of the suffering mom of the movie’s female lead, Nina, a troubled teen who was a rebel, a budding rock singer who would form a friendship with a good-looking deaf-mute dancer, much to the chagrin of her parents (especially her authoritarian dad). Zoe Sandejas, Mike’s beautiful and talented daughter, would be playing the lead. Her leading man would be a young actor (and true-to-life hearing-impaired artist from St. Benilde) Rome Mallari, whom I had the pleasure of knowing from his work in Gantimpala Theater Foundation (where I was playing lead for classics like “Florante at Laura” and “Kanser: Noli Me Tangere”).\r\n\r\nOver the course of the next few weeks, we would shoot in locations such as La Salle Greenhills and in Baguio.\r\n\r\nThe experience was pretty much like being on the set with college friends on a project that everyone was pulling for and believed in: we were made aware of Mike’s vision and were working in concert towards realizing that vision and committing it to film.\r\n\r\nEventually, we would be rewarded during the Cinemalaya awards night (the film took home the Audience’s Choice and National Council for Children’s Television Awards, plus the Balanghai Trophy for Best Musical Score), other awards from other bodies including recognition for Rome and for the Musical Score, and an extended run in several campuses and other venues.\r\n\r\nActing in this “Cinemalaya” film made me realize some things:\r\n<ol style=\"margin-left: 20px;\">\r\n 	<li>A CINEMALAYA FILM is usually fueled by the very personal vision of the filmmaker. Since he himself was producing the movie, Mike had full creative control, without the dictates of a studio or a mainstream producer. The film he was creating, it turns out, also resonated with him on a deep, personal basis – touching on matters that were very real to him, his family and the relationships that governed this family.</li>\r\n 	<li>NOTHING IS AS PLEASURABLE AS WORKING WITH FAMILIAR PEOPLE, OR A COMPANY THAT WOULD BECOME FRIENDS. Mike had commissioned his long-time friends to be part of the cast, specifically the adult characters. It was good to be working again with old friends and co-workers such as singer and film, TV and theater actor Robert Sena, who was playing the sensitive psychologist whom Zoe’s parents would consult when she threatens to spin away from their reach, and Assistant Director, industry veteran Direk Armando Reyes, whom I had the pleasure of working with in some films of Adolfo Alix, Jr. Lorenzo (Tata) Mara, former model and erstwhile leading man of many films in the 80s and 90s, was playing the role of the Dad, a figure whose face is never seen, selected for his commanding voice, a presence who instills so much fear and resentment in his daughter. His wife, Angie, was a former fellow TV commercial model of mine, who now heads her own Talent Agency. He and I rode up to Baguio together and shared a late meal at Pizza Volante upon getting there before proceeding to our quarters. Up to now, he is a constant textmate, since Tata is fond of sharing inspirational quotes from the Bible. A sad note: on our way back to Manila, Tata got word that Star Cinema director Cathy Garcia-Molina, whom we left shooting in the Summer Capital, had just lost her husband in a biking accident on location. From time to time I see Zoe in my FB feeds and in her various gigs as model and performer.</li>\r\n 	<li>AS EXPECTED, THE PACE IS NOT AS PUNISHING AS IN MAINSTREAM TV OR FILM. Although definitely working on a budget, we were not rushing to catch an episode for airing that same day, nor were we being monitored by the Producer and being hurried to finish immediately (the Producer was right there, behind the camera).</li>\r\n 	<li>YOUTH-ORIENTED FILMS HAVE A STRONG AND CONSIDERABLE MARKET IN CINEMALAYA. Students all over the country have become true fans of the two leads and the film. Fortunately, the leads deliver engaging and heartfelt performances, have strong chemistry together and are both easy on the eyes. And the film turned out to be a real delight: by turns humorous, dramatic, romantic and simply charming. Which brings me to:</li>\r\n 	<li>A CROWD-PLEASING CINEMALAYA FILM IS A JOY TO BE PART OF. As in any festival, it’s a great feeling being part of an audience that gets caught up in the story you are telling. And since the festival runs for sometime, you become part of a movie-going community that shares your pride in your work… just as you become part of the other actors’ and companies’ journey.</li>\r\n 	<li>INDUSTRY VETERANS AND CO-WORKERS WILL BE THE FIRST TO SHOW THEIR APPRECIATION FOR YOUR WORK. Hit filmmaker Direk Joey Javier Reyes enthused, “THIS should be the kind of film that Star Cinema is producing!” when I saw him right after our screening. He said the film was so fresh and just lovely. Actor and director Rowell Santiago saw it at a later time but made sure to call on the phone just to say he liked the film very much. Such generous comments from respected professionals are, to say the least, heart-warming.</li>\r\n 	<li>FOOD IS STILL THE CHOICE OF BONDING ACTIVITY – ON ANY SET. Sharing hearty meals will always draw a family closer together, and this is very true on the set, where you are also sharing a vision, the challenges and the exhilaration of completing every scene together.</li>\r\n 	<li>AND THE TALENT FEE IS THE LAST THING YOU THINK OF WHEN YOU ARE ENJOYING DOING A PROJECT. This is the BS-free truth.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nA recent viewing of some clips in this nine year old film made me realize how its charm holds up to this day. It’s still a story worth watching, and a movie with its heart in the right place.\r\n\r\nAnd making it was a truly delightful Cinemalaya experience.', 'Acting for Cinemalaya Made Me Realize...', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '66-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:40:46', '2018-03-20 14:40:46', '', 66, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/66-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(158, 1, '2018-03-20 10:41:07', '2018-03-20 14:41:07', 'I’ve supported Cinemalaya for about 7 yrs now, and I’ve seen a drastic change on concepts.\r\n\r\nIn the past years, Cinemalaya offered a platform for talented independent filmmakers however progressed to a space for art. For us Filipinos, family is where we’ll always have a soft spot for and from 2008, the storylines has always been limited - rather reserved. Cinemalaya through the years have escalated to be the landscape of family, politics, sex, drugs, religion and I would say filmmakers started playing around the storylines of these issues in 2012, at least for me when I started seeing the “abstract”. I came across this indie film called “Ang Nawawala” by Marie Jamora and if anyone would have take a look on their poster it would look like a movie for hipsters. Is it about family?<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-72\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture21.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"337\" />\r\n\r\nYes. Is there drama? Yes. Romance? Yes. Everyone looks for “not so brilliant but maybe new” “yung bago naman, puro ganun naman storya eh boy meets girl ends up or doesn’t end up together one dies or one has cancer and survives then becomes a family person”  YES THIS IS EXACTLY THE FRONT OF “Ang Nawawala”. What I liked about it is the story played along the lines of “yes we are predictable” and “nope that’s not what I expected”. The story is about a boy who saw his twin die in front of his eyes. The boy comes back home from abroad to a dysfunctional family. The boy finds himself wanting to fix his family by talking/ consulting to his dead twin.  He highlights the silences that do exist in long drawn bouts with grief.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-73\" src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/Picture22.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"957\" height=\"535\" />\r\n\r\nThe story shows the complexity of a family that goes through a circumstance and how they can get out of it - how they help themselves. Gibson (the main character in the story), is the main focus of the story.  Yes the film gave out romantic cliches and how a normal teenager should act but this is my personal ideal storyline for family concept. The story shows the characters going through emotional hardship, to a point where each of them gave up their dreams. One day, the dad of Gibson sneaks inside his room and find his computer open with thumbnails of videos. If I didn’t mention, Gibson walks around with a camera in the story - that’s why perception from viewers of the film is that it could be hipster. Anyway, to cut the chase the dad opens the videos and they were all moments of joy, joy that is something to cry a waterfall about - literally. The scene cuts to Gibson behind his camera taking those moments and he closes his eyes to feel it. This is for me the perfect rendition (OUT OF ANYTHING ELSE IN FAMILIAL MOVIES) of HURT in the family is - losing someone and could not get out the circumstance.  This boy keeps beautiful moments with him, hoping for change in his family. At the end, it did not have that big family hug playing “seasons of love in the background” NO!. RATHER, the ending is remarkable. The director ended it with just the mom and Gibson - no dad, and two sisters in the frame. They were all busy in outside watching the fireworks, and Gibson goes inside the room of his mom. While his mom is sleeping he picks her up on his lap, watching TV of New year coverage on the screen. Gibson closes his eyes, without his camera and speaks.\r\n\r\nFamily-oriented films are notorious for “not bagging the award” because obviously in watching a slice of life kind of films production does not concentrate on visuals, editing and other technical stuff unless it is like the concept of “Ang Nawawala”. The impact of these films for a viewer’s standpoint is something they would rather brew at the back of their heads after watching, or something they just forget. Family-oriented films become impactful (at least for me personally) if 1) there’s a twist 2)they don’t end up singing and hugging in front of a grand piano at the end 3) a dash of humor. Filipinos are known for being very festive, creative and looking for a film that fits them (not only referring to family oriented movies but the diversity of movie genres as well) however, at ending credits of every film that we watch, no matter how much twist and turns (abstract, creativity, complexity of production) , upside downs,  family is a place that is our home for Filipinos and it is a concept we all yearn to see.', 'Cinemalaya Feels Like Home', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '70-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:41:07', '2018-03-20 14:41:07', '', 70, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/70-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
