(159, 1, '2018-03-20 10:41:27', '2018-03-20 14:41:27', 'Cinemalaya is known to welcome entries that the objectives are to raise awareness of social issue relevance, highlight the political injustice present in the society and jar away from the typical mainstream movies that are popularly shown in the country. As someone who is not a fan of supporting mainstream Filipino movies, the expectations I have for Cinemalaya is quite high. Knowing that filmmakers are free to submit what they have to offer, I\'m very much pleased with seeing the LGBT community be a part of the characters. One of the films I have watched from Cinemalaya is entitled <em><i>Ang Pagdadalaga ni Maximo Oliveros, </i></em>which was directed by Auraeus Solito. The movie starred a 12-year-old boy named Maxi. Coming from the title, it is about the coming of age of a homosexual boy. The story revolved around how Maxi\'s family, his social status and his attitude towards whatever situation he is faced. There are a lot of films that were shown in Cinemalaya that are about Homosexuality. In fact, they populate almost all of the influential personalities in the country. These are Vice Ganda, BJ Pascual, Congresswoman Geraldine Roman and Rajo Laurel. As you might not have noticed, the ones that are mentioned are only those who are gay and transgender women. The representation and the acceptance of lesbians in country are not very popular. There are actually a lot of misconceptions about the lesbian community. One of its stereotypes is that a lesbian automatically wants to look like a boy, act like a boy and talk like a boy. Yes, the LGBT community is accepted in the country thus films like Ang Pagdadalaga ni Maximo Oliveros but it\'s quite unfortunate that there aren\'t a lot of lesbian characters in Cinemalaya not as quite often as gay characters. I guess how I view the diverse genre entries of Cinemalaya is that it still needs more representations of other groups in the society.', 'A Different View On The LGBT Cinemalaya Films', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '78-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:41:27', '2018-03-20 14:41:27', '', 78, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/78-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(160, 1, '2018-03-20 10:41:45', '2018-03-20 14:41:45', 'The great thing about Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival for me is that it is the most honest film festival in the Philippines. It is honest in the sense that filmmakers do not produce Cinemalaya films in order to make so much money. All of the stories that were created are from the heart. Every filmmaker, whether they win or not, they fabricated a movie that is sincere and not just to win. I am glad because I have seen Cinemalaya from the very beginning. It started from a small-scale until it reached this year. Usually Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival is held during the month of August when the rain pours which results to the people not being able to support the screenings of the films nevertheless through the years.. 13 great years, Cinemalaya has become a major force. The fact that some independent filmmakers measure their success when they are already producing mainstream movies nonetheless maybe it’s really how careers go or history folds. There is nothing wrong with mainstream cinema but I hope that the filmmakers who have entered the industry could always go back to making independent films. The end goal is not producing a low budget film to receive an award, or for you to be well known nor to make so much money. I don’t think that should be the final purpose of any filmmaker. I’m glad that Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival has given their audience a choice wherein people can watch their films that were produced without pressure for commercial viability. ', 'Cinemalaya As The Most Honest Film Festival in the Philippines', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '129-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:41:45', '2018-03-20 14:41:45', '', 129, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/129-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(161, 1, '2018-03-20 10:42:01', '2018-03-20 14:42:01', 'A Classic cinemalaya film from back in 2005, Ang Pagdadalaga ni Maximo Oliveros is a beautiful film by Auraeous Solito. A 12 year old Maximo Oliveros is from the slums in Manila. Maximo, lovingly referred to by his neighbors as Maxi, is gay. Despite his traditionally unaccepted sexual orientation, he is tenderly taken care of by his doting father and two older brothers. Maxi\'s family is engaged in a life of crime and monkey business ranging from peddling illegal drugs to pick-pocketing cellular phones. Personally, this film is the most remarkable LGBT related movie I’ve ever seen. And I wasn’t the only one with the same sentiments. Its influence was so widespread that they had to show and bring it to Manhattan for international screening. In a nutshell, it talks about how a young boy can live his life normally without the oftentimes heavy burden of hiding one’s sexuality. This story brings out a very powerful voice for the LGBT community wherein it showed the complexity of the elements involved in the concepts of “homosexuality” and “ innocence”. These complexities were highlighted in the simple story of a young boy exposed to corruption and despondency. Maxi showed truthfulness and heart all throughout the film. It speaks toward a reality we live in now, which wasn’t the case at the time. The reality being that one’s sexual orientation is not “just a phase” and doesn’t need to affect the way people around you interact with you. Maxi is not defined by his sexuality, but simply by his person and everyone around him treats him as exactly what he is - a good, and honest little boy. There are no formal rites of passage, no overly elaborate plot that pushes him to grow up and out of his puppy love feelings for the policeman he has a crush on. Audiences may misunderstand the title “The Blossoming”, however in the story Maxi\'s metamorphic blossoming results from what essentially is an innocent crush that curiously develops into an ambiguous attraction. This being from the very first Cinemalaya film festival, was a brave move considering the social climate of the Philippines toward LGBT culture at the time. For many years, being “bakla” or “tomboy” in Philippine media would always have a comedic connotation - the overly rambunctious cross-dressing gay and the virgin tomboy awaiting a real man’s touch. And for many years, this form of “toleration” of the LGBT community was all the representation there was in Philippine society. But through films like this, the truth of the LGBT community’s story is brought out of the shadows and onto the silver screen for all to open their eyes. It is thanks to this movie that many more entries into the Cinemalaya film festival were able to be transparent about sexuality - a most taboo discussion for a traditionally Catholic country. Especially through the perspective of an innocent child just going through life, experiencing every “normal” encounter in a young person’s life - like a simple crush. This simply told story about a little crush will always represent the truth of humanity - no matter who we are and where we come from we all deserve to love.', 'How Brave, Maxi', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '132-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:42:01', '2018-03-20 14:42:01', '', 132, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/132-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(162, 1, '2018-03-20 10:42:16', '2018-03-20 14:42:16', 'In a country where Catholicism dominates, beliefs and values restrict one\'s ability to validate their sexuality. There are pros and cons in so many aspects of this norm and yet it is obvious that these affect how the society views the people who show their indifference from what is suppose to be accepted. \r\n\r\nWhen we talk about the specifics, majority of the Filipinos acknowledge the existence of the LGBT community however their actions and behavior do not reciprocate this. It may seem as if it is accepted just because many of the LGBT community already dominate certain fields but the discrimination and disgust is still present. As someone who sees the world in a totally different angle, which is at the losing end of the indiscretion happening in the society, it is unavoidable to feel outcasted and burdened. Furthermore, it hinders the LGBT group to be harmonious with the rest of the community. \r\n	\r\nThere are a number of people from the LGBT community who try to jar away from feeling secluded; they use many channels such as media to change the system. These brave souls use their intellect and capabilities for the society to be proven wrong. Nowadays, unjust treatment to the LGBT members are being noticed and are given attention to in such a way that more and more individuals are siding on them. \r\n	\r\nOne way of supporting this notion is featuring this topic in films. In Cinemalaya, the rainbow theme is becoming a trend to the industry. More directors and writers draw attention to the topic and make characters about it. FIlms such as Translacion: Ang Paglalakad sa Altar ng Alanganin, Ang Pagdadalaga ni Maximo Oliveros, Kasal, and many more. \r\n	\r\nIt relieves many Filipinos who are part of the LGBT population because it gives hope and recognition that these individuals are no different than the rest of the straight community. At the same time, it sends off a message that the artists are being part of a movement where these so called \"different\" people are welcome and should not be ashamed of who they are. It brings joy to those who hide in the shadows- afraid to be truly who they are. \r\n\r\nCinemalaya is indeed a very special medium to include everyone who is anyone and is a platform that stands for the people who cannot stand for themselves. \r\n', 'Cinemalaya: Not Just a Festival but also a Movement', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '135-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 10:42:16', '2018-03-20 14:42:16', '', 135, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/135-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(163, 1, '2018-03-20 16:14:48', '2018-03-20 20:14:48', '<style>.entry-header{display: none;}</style>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1212.jpg\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: \"bebas\";\">Mark Meily</strong>Mark is a multi-awarded filmmaker. He is the director of Donor (2010) in Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival. He won the award for Best Cinematography for his film. His feature films have been presented at the film festivals of Deauville, Hawaii, Seattle, Goteborg, Marrakech, Montreal, Busan, Fukuoka and Brussels.\r\nMark is also a film educator.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1213.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: \"bebas\";\">Dennis Marasigan</strong>Dennis is an actor, writer, filmmaker and producer. He started acting in theater and later on worked in the film industry. Dennis submitted two (2) films in Cinemalaya entitled, “Vox Populi” (2010) and “Tukso” (2007). He is the director of Tukso which has won the award for Best Screenplay in the year 2007 in Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1214.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: \"bebas\";\">Adriana Agcaoili</strong>Adriana is writer, host and theater and film actor. She was involved in Cinemalaya in 2009 as an actress in Mike Sandejas’ film “Dinig Sana Kita”. The film went on to win these awards in the festival: Audience’s Choice and Balanghai Trophy for Best Musical Score, National Council for Children’s Television Award, as well as the Star Award for New Movie Actor of the Year for the male lead, Romalito Mallari, a real hearing-impaired dancer and actor, and was a Gawad Urian nominee for Best Music. In 2013, she was the Awards Night event writer.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1215.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: \"bebas\";\">Franz Valenzuela</strong>Franz is an amateur filmmaker and a Cinemalaya enthusiast since 2007. She has finished a Bachelor’s Degree on Media Production. She has exprienced directing short films when she was in college. In the year 2017, Franz has received the award for Best Cinematography in her college for her short film entitled “Check-In”. Currently, she is based in New York City to pursue her filmmaking career.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1216.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: \"bebas\";\">Gia Gumisad</strong>Gia is currently taking Communications in college. She is a Cinemalaya Enthusiats since 2014. Often times, she would write reviews on the Cinemalaya films that she has watched. Gia has also took up Theater Arts in University of the Philippines - Diliman. She has a lot of experience when it comes to theater acting, hosting, and performing.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'The Contributors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '99-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 16:14:48', '2018-03-20 20:14:48', '', 99, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/99-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(164, 1, '2018-03-20 16:15:28', '2018-03-20 20:15:28', '<style>.entry-header{display: none;}</style>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1212.jpg\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: bebas;\">Mark Meily</strong>Mark is a multi-awarded filmmaker. He is the director of Donor (2010) in Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival. He won the award for Best Cinematography for his film. His feature films have been presented at the film festivals of Deauville, Hawaii, Seattle, Goteborg, Marrakech, Montreal, Busan, Fukuoka and Brussels.\r\nMark is also a film educator.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1213.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: bebas;\">Dennis Marasigan</strong>Dennis is an actor, writer, filmmaker and producer. He started acting in theater and later on worked in the film industry. Dennis submitted two (2) films in Cinemalaya entitled, “Vox Populi” (2010) and “Tukso” (2007). He is the director of Tukso which has won the award for Best Screenplay in the year 2007 in Cinemalaya Independent Film Festival.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1214.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: bebas;\">Adriana Agcaoili</strong>Adriana is writer, host and theater and film actor. She was involved in Cinemalaya in 2009 as an actress in Mike Sandejas’ film “Dinig Sana Kita”. The film went on to win these awards in the festival: Audience’s Choice and Balanghai Trophy for Best Musical Score, National Council for Children’s Television Award, as well as the Star Award for New Movie Actor of the Year for the male lead, Romalito Mallari, a real hearing-impaired dancer and actor, and was a Gawad Urian nominee for Best Music. In 2013, she was the Awards Night event writer.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1215.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family:bebas;\">Franz Valenzuela</strong>Franz is an amateur filmmaker and a Cinemalaya enthusiast since 2007. She has finished a Bachelor’s Degree on Media Production. She has exprienced directing short films when she was in college. In the year 2017, Franz has received the award for Best Cinematography in her college for her short film entitled “Check-In”. Currently, she is based in New York City to pursue her filmmaking career.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"row\" style=\"margin-bottom: 30px\">\r\n<div class=\"col-md-3\"><img src=\"http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/1216.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"col-md-9\"><strong style=\"font-size: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px; display: block; font-family: bebas;\">Gia Gumisad</strong>Gia is currently taking Communications in college. She is a Cinemalaya Enthusiats since 2014. Often times, she would write reviews on the Cinemalaya films that she has watched. Gia has also took up Theater Arts in University of the Philippines - Diliman. She has a lot of experience when it comes to theater acting, hosting, and performing.\r\n</div>\r\n</div>', 'The Contributors', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '99-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-03-20 16:15:28', '2018-03-20 20:15:28', '', 99, 'http://throughtheeyes.info/iteration1/article/99-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
